<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910920-0083</DOCNO><DOCID>910920-0083.</DOCID><HL>   Severance Plan   Is Set By Chemical,   Manufacturers   ----   By Steven Lipin   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7A</SO><CO>   BAC CHL MHC SPC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MAJOR MONEY CENTER BANKS (BAN)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)WESTERN U.S. BANKS (BAW)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   It may be small consolation to them, but the 6,200employees of Chemical Banking Corp. and Manufacturers HanoverCorp. who will lose their jobs because of the pending mergerwill receive one of the banking industry's more generousseverance packages.   Both banks told employees yesterday through companynewsletters that those to be dismissed will receive threeweeks of salary and benefits for each year of employment.Compensation experts say that the norm in cutbacks in thebanking industry has been one to two weeks for each year ofservice.</LP><TEXT>   The two institutions have a combined total of 45,000employees and only a handful have been dismissed so far. Thecost of the severance agreements will account for between$300 million and $320 million of the $550 millionrestructuring charge the new Chemical Banking Corp. will takeafter completing the merger, the companies have toldanalysts.   The restructuring charge is expected to be taken at theend of the fourth quarter. But the staff cuts could take aslong as two years, the companies said in a meeting withanalysts.   The package would grant a minimum of eight weeks ofseverance, thus giving extra compensation for neweremployees, and a maximum of 52 weeks. Morever, 25-yearveterans of the two banking companies will receive anadditional six months of salary, a spokeswoman said.   Employees of the two institutions have been waiting tohear details of the severance package, and many expect thepink slips to follow soon.   &quot;People have been on the edge of their desks waiting forthis,&quot; said one bank official of the announcement. &quot;Needlessto say, it's been widely read.&quot;   By way of comparison, Citicorp's severance packageannounced in March offered two weeks of salary per year ofwork, with a minimum of four weeks and a maximum of 52 weeks.Roughly 5,000 of the 7,000 expected to be dismissed have beenlet go to date, a spokeswoman said.   Experts in compensation say the package is very generous,given the current economic climate. Many financialinstitutions give no more than one week of salary for everyyear of employment.   &quot;It sounds like a generous compensation package for afinancial institution to give its people in today's economy,&quot;said Joseph H. McCann III, managing director at the WhitneyGroup, an executive search firm based in New York.&quot; It stacksup well with other agreements,&quot; he added.   Still, the severance package of the merger betweenSecurity Pacific Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. is even sweeter.Employees below the level of senior vice president willreceive three weeks of compensation per year of service, witha minimum of 12 weeks and a maximum of 78 weeks.</TEXT></DOC>